ICBC, Foxconn, Henderson, PetroChina: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-05-23T00:35:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-23/icbc-foxconn-henderson-petrochina-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  rose 0.2 percent to 23,199.39. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, gained 0.1 percent to 12,947.94.  Banks: China’s banking system requires further
strengthening of its risk management, Fan Wenzhong, director-
general of the China Banking Regulatory Commission, said at a
forum in  Shanghai  on May 21. Even though local lenders are
significantly better positioned than their global peers in terms
of capital adequacy ratios and liquidity, more risk management
is “prudent,” Fan said.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (601398)  Ltd. (1398 HK), the
nation’s biggest lender, was unchanged at HK$6.40.  China
Construction Bank Corp. (939) , (939 HK) the nation’s No. 2 lender by
market value, gained 0.3 percent to HK$7.23.  Developers: Registered new home sales in Hong Kong may
total 1,800 this month, a 13-month high, as developments offered
last month lured homeowners and speculators, Centaline Property
Agency Ltd. said in an e-mailed statement.  This month’s transactions may be worth a combined HK$14
billion ($1.8 billion), a seven-month high and 45 percent more
than April, Centaline Research Director Wong Leung-sing
estimated in the statement.  Henderson Land Development Co. (12 HK), the builder
controlled by billionaire Lee Shau-kee, rose 0.1 percent to
HK$51.35.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK), the world’s
biggest developer, fell 0.5 percent to HK$120.60.  Foxconn International Holdings Ltd. (2038)  (2038 HK): Foxconn
Technology Group, maker of Apple Inc.’s iPhone and Dell Inc.
computers, had an explosion and fire at a plant in southwest
China’s Sichuan province on May 20 that killed two people and
injured 16. Foxconn International, the Hong Kong-listed unit of
the Foxconn Technology Group, declined 1.2 percent to HK$4.20.  Huadian Power International Corp. (1071 HK): The state-
owned Chinese electricity company said it plans to raise as much
as 2.1 billion yuan ($323 million) selling new domestic shares
to investors. The new shares will represent about 11.2 percent
of existing issued A-shares and 8.9 percent of total existing
issued share capital, Huadian said. The stock slumped 4.5
percent to HK$1.69.  Hutchison Whampoa Ltd. (13)  (13 HK): The company’s 3 Group
business, which offers 3G, or third-generation, mobile-phone
services, will be profitable this year, Managing Director
Canning Fok said. Hutchison Whampoa, billionaire  Li Ka-shing ’s
biggest company, climbed 0.1 percent to HK$87.15.  PetroChina Co. (857 HK): China’s largest oil company shut
its Dalian refinery for maintenance until the end of June,
parent China National Petroleum Corp. said in its online
newsletter. The stock advanced 0.2 percent to HK$10.66.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Tokyo at 
